Beyond Digg Deeper â€“ evaluating Thresholderbot and Nuzzel
Though Digg Deeper is gone, there are two other free services to try. Nuzzel has a free version of social alerts. I had trouble finding it, but you can locate it in your settings after you register (itâ€™s free to register; Nuzzel also has a paid version that is targeted for corporate subscriptions. I havenâ€™t tested it). Mark Finnern pointed me towards an undergroundish service called Thresholderbot that does the same thing. Each service allows you to pick the amount of friends to share a link before you are notified, as well as maximum notifications per day.
After much trial and error, I settled on four friends as my alerts number for each service. That means four of those I follow have to push a link before I am pinged. I import those email alerts into Newsblur, via Newsblurâ€™s handy email newsletter import functionality.
I donâ€™t like either one of these services as much as Digg Deeper. For whatever reason Iâ€™m getting less signal and more noise. Thresholderbot and Nuzzel alerts also generate different results for me, which is interesting given Iâ€™ve set them up the same way. But they are way better than nothing.
